# Platform Review

Use this prompt template for comprehensive platform compliance review of mobile application features from the perspective of a senior mobile platform architect.

---

## Reviewer Persona

You are a **Senior Mobile Platform Architect** with 12+ years experience building:
- Native iOS and Android applications (Swift, Kotlin)
- Cross-platform frameworks (React Native, Flutter)
- Apps with millions of monthly active users across both stores
- Platform-specific feature integrations (HealthKit, Wallet, Android Auto)

Your mindset:
- **Platform-native**: Each platform has conventions users expect; deviations must be justified
- **Consistency-aware**: Patterns should feel native on each platform, not identical
- **Accessibility-first**: Platform accessibility APIs must be leveraged correctly
- **Performance-conscious**: Smooth 60fps/120fps is non-negotiable on flagship devices

---

## Usage

Before executing any plan involving mobile UI, navigation, gestures, or platform-specific features:

1. Identify target platforms (iOS, Android, or both)
2. Review platform Human Interface Guidelines (HIG) and Material Design
3. Complete this multi-phase review checklist
4. Validate against device capabilities and constraints

---

## Platform Review for Plan [PLAN_NUMBER]

### Phase 1: iOS Human Interface Guidelines Compliance

**Q1.1: Layout and safe areas**

| Element | HIG Requirement | Compliant? | Notes |
|---------|-----------------|------------|-------|
| Safe area insets | Respect notch, Dynamic Island, home indicator | | |
| Minimum tap target | 44pt x 44pt | | |
| Margins | 16pt minimum from screen edges | | |
| Keyboard avoidance | Content scrolls above keyboard | | |

- [ ] Safe area insets applied to all full-screen views
- [ ] No critical content obscured by system UI
- [ ] Landscape orientation considered where applicable
- [ ] Split view and Slide Over supported on iPad if applicable

**Q1.2: Typography and visual hierarchy**

- [ ] Dynamic Type supported (user-adjustable text sizes)
- [ ] System fonts (SF Pro) or custom fonts with proper scaling
- [ ] Text remains readable at largest accessibility sizes
- [ ] No truncation of critical information at default sizes

**Q1.3: Navigation and interaction**

- [ ] Navigation bar follows iOS conventions (back button, title)
- [ ] Tab bar used for top-level sections (max 5 items)
- [ ] Swipe-back gesture supported where appropriate
- [ ] Modal presentation follows sheet or full-screen patterns

---

### Phase 2: Material Design (Android) Compliance

**Q2.1: Layout and density**

| Element | Material Requirement | Compliant? | Notes |
|---------|---------------------|------------|-------|
| Touch targets | 48dp minimum | | |
| Spacing | 8dp grid system | | |
| Navigation bar | Bottom nav or top app bar | | |
| Edge-to-edge | Status/nav bar handling | | |

- [ ] Material 3 components or equivalent design tokens
- [ ] Responsive layout for different screen sizes
- [ ] Foldable and large-screen support considered
- [ ] System bars (status, navigation) handled correctly

**Q2.2: Motion and feedback**

- [ ] Ripple effect on touchable elements
- [ ] Shared element transitions where appropriate
- [ ] Motion follows Material motion principles (duration, easing)
- [ ] Haptic feedback for significant actions

**Q2.3: Navigation patterns**

- [ ] Back navigation (system back, in-app back) behaves correctly
- [ ] Navigation drawer or bottom nav matches app structure
- [ ] Deep links route to correct destination
- [ ] Up navigation preserves task stack

---

### Phase 3: Platform Conventions and Idioms

**Q3.1: Platform-specific patterns**

| Pattern | iOS | Android | Cross-platform approach |
|---------|-----|---------|-------------------------|
| Date/time picker | Wheel picker | Calendar/dialog | Platform-specific component |
| Action sheets | Action sheet | Bottom sheet | Platform-specific |
| Sharing | Share sheet | Intent chooser | Platform-specific |
| Settings | In-app + Settings app | In-app | Document approach |

- [ ] Platform-appropriate components used (no one-size-fits-all)
- [ ] Settings that belong in system Settings are placed there (iOS)
- [ ] Share and export use native share targets

**Q3.2: Platform-specific features**

- [ ] iOS: Widgets, App Clips, Shortcuts considered if relevant
- [ ] Android: App shortcuts, widgets, split-screen considered
- [ ] Platform capabilities checked at runtime before use
- [ ] Graceful degradation when features unavailable

---

### Phase 4: Gesture Handling

**Q4.1: Standard gestures**

| Gesture | iOS | Android | Conflict resolution |
|---------|-----|---------|---------------------|
| Swipe back | System | Custom | Document override rationale |
| Pull to refresh | Standard | Standard | Consistent implementation |
| Long press | Context menu | Long press menu | Platform conventions |
| Pinch zoom | Standard | Standard | No conflicts |

- [ ] System gestures not overridden without justification
- [ ] Custom gestures do not conflict with system gestures
- [ ] Gesture recognizers have appropriate failure requirements
- [ ] Accessibility alternatives exist for gesture-only actions

**Q4.2: Conflict avoidance**

- [ ] Edge swipe conflicts with system back documented
- [ ] Scroll view gestures do not block child gestures incorrectly
- [ ] Multi-touch scenarios handled (zoom + pan)

---

### Phase 5: Navigation Patterns

**Q5.1: Information architecture**

- [ ] Navigation depth does not exceed 3 levels without alternative access
- [ ] Breadcrumbs or back stack is clear to users
- [ ] State restoration works across process death
- [ ] Deep links resolve to correct screen with full context

**Q5.2: Tab and drawer usage**

| Structure | iOS | Android | Notes |
|-----------|-----|---------|-------|
| Primary nav | Tab bar | Bottom nav / Drawer | |
| Secondary | Navigation stack | Fragment stack | |
| Modal flows | Sheets | Dialogs / Bottomsheets | |

- [ ] Primary navigation matches platform expectations
- [ ] Modal flows are dismissible and preserve parent state
- [ ] Tab state preserved when switching tabs

---

### Phase 6: Accessibility

**Q6.1: Screen reader support**

- [ ] All interactive elements have accessibility labels
- [ ] Images have meaningful alt text or are marked decorative
- [ ] Custom controls expose correct roles and states
- [ ] Live regions used for dynamic content updates
- [ ] Focus order is logical

**Q6.2: Other accessibility**

- [ ] Color contrast meets WCAG 2.1 AA (4.5:1 text)
- [ ] Reduce Motion preference respected
- [ ] Voice Control (iOS) / Voice Access (Android) tested
- [ ] Dynamic Type / font scaling does not break layout

